WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.180 --> 00:00:09.322
Professor Robert Shiller:
Today I want to spend--The

00:00:09.322 --> 00:00:15.571
title of today's lecture is:
The Universal Principle of Risk

00:00:15.571 --> 00:00:21.140
Management,
Pooling and the Hedging of Risk.

00:00:21.140 --> 00:00:25.008
What I'm really referring to is
what I think is the very

00:00:25.008 --> 00:00:29.440
original, the deep concept that
underlies theoretical finance--I

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:34.111
wanted to get that first.
It really is probability theory

00:00:34.111 --> 00:00:38.610
and the idea of spreading risk
through risk pooling.

00:00:38.610 --> 00:00:44.553
So, this idea is an
intellectual construct that

00:00:44.553 --> 00:00:51.659
appeared at a certain point in
history and it has had an

00:00:51.659 --> 00:00:59.800
amazing number of applications
and finance is one of these.

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:03.829
Some of you--This incidentally
will be a more technical of my

00:01:03.829 --> 00:01:07.926
lectures and it's a little bit
unfortunate that it comes early

00:01:07.926 --> 00:01:10.684
in the semester.
For those of you who have had a

00:01:10.684 --> 00:01:12.967
course in probability and
statistics, there will be

00:01:12.967 --> 00:01:15.951
nothing new here.
Well, nothing in terms of the

00:01:15.951 --> 00:01:18.220
math.
The probability theory is new.

00:01:18.220 --> 00:01:21.374
Others though,
I want to tell you that it

00:01:21.374 --> 00:01:26.184
doesn't--if you're shopping--I
had a student come by yesterday

00:01:26.184 --> 00:01:30.916
and ask--he's a little rusty in
his math skills--if he should

00:01:30.916 --> 00:01:34.027
take this course.
I said, "Well if you can

00:01:34.027 --> 00:01:36.406
understand tomorrow's
lecture--that's today's

00:01:36.406 --> 00:01:38.840
lecture--then you should have no
problem."

00:01:42.959 --> 00:01:47.670
I want to start with the
concept of probability.

00:01:50.910 --> 00:01:53.040
Do you know what a probability
is?

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:58.290
We attach a probability to an
event.

00:01:58.290 --> 00:02:02.955
What is the probability that
the stock market will go up this

00:02:02.955 --> 00:02:07.198
year?
I would say--my personal

00:02:07.198 --> 00:02:12.771
probability is .45.
That's because I'm a bear

00:02:12.771 --> 00:02:16.159
but--Do you know what that
means?

00:02:16.159 --> 00:02:20.678
That 45 times out of 100 the
stock market will go up and the

00:02:20.678 --> 00:02:25.350
other 55 times out of 100 it
will stay the same or go down.

00:02:25.350 --> 00:02:31.282
That's a probability.
Now, you're familiar with that

00:02:31.282 --> 00:02:35.326
concept, right?
If someone says the probability

00:02:35.326 --> 00:02:39.150
is .55 or .45,
well you know what that means.

00:02:39.150 --> 00:02:45.208
I want to emphasize that it
hasn't always been that way and

00:02:45.208 --> 00:02:51.789
that probability is really a
concept that arose in the 1600s.

00:02:51.789 --> 00:02:55.759
Before that,
nobody ever said that.

00:02:55.759 --> 00:02:59.317
Ian Hacking,
who wrote a history of

00:02:59.317 --> 00:03:03.607
probability theory,
searched through world

00:03:03.607 --> 00:03:09.781
literature for any reference to
a probability and could find

00:03:09.781 --> 00:03:15.819
none anywhere before 1600.
There was an intellectual leap

00:03:15.819 --> 00:03:21.017
that occurred in the seventeenth
century and it became very

00:03:21.017 --> 00:03:25.409
fashionable to talk in terms of
probabilities.

00:03:25.409 --> 00:03:28.720
It spread throughout the
world--the idea of quoting

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:32.000
probabilities.
But it was--It's funny that

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.620
such a simple idea hadn't been
used before.

00:03:35.620 --> 00:03:39.488
Hacking points out that the
word probability--or

00:03:39.488 --> 00:03:43.440
probable--was already in the
English language.

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:48.789
In fact, Shakespeare used it,
but what do you think it meant?

00:03:48.789 --> 00:03:53.683
He gives an example of a young
woman, who was describing a man

00:03:53.683 --> 00:03:55.929
that she liked,
and she said,

00:03:55.929 --> 00:04:00.020
I like him very much,
I find him very probable.

00:04:00.020 --> 00:04:03.409
What do you think she means?
Can someone answer that?

00:04:03.409 --> 00:04:07.350
Does anyone know Elizabethan
English well enough to tell me?

00:04:07.350 --> 00:04:13.310
What is a probable young man?
I'm asking for an answer.

00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:21.320
It sounds like people have no
idea.

00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:26.320
Can anyone venture a guess?
No one wants to venture a guess?

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:30.348
Student: fertile?
Professor Robert

00:04:30.348 --> 00:04:33.350
Shiller: That he can father
children?

00:04:33.350 --> 00:04:39.019
I don't think that's what she
meant but maybe.

00:04:39.019 --> 00:04:46.209
No, what apparently she meant
is trustworthy.

00:04:46.209 --> 00:04:48.889
That's a very important quality
in a person I suppose.

00:04:48.889 --> 00:04:53.294
So, if something is probable
you mean that you can trust it

00:04:53.294 --> 00:04:56.560
and so probability means
trustworthiness.

00:04:56.560 --> 00:05:01.522
You can see how they moved from
that definition of probability

00:05:01.522 --> 00:05:03.800
to the current definition.

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:09.949
But Ian Hacking,
being a good historian,

00:05:09.949 --> 00:05:14.298
thought that someone must have
had some concept of probability

00:05:14.298 --> 00:05:17.297
going before,
even if they didn't quote it as

00:05:17.297 --> 00:05:20.758
a number the way--it must have
been in their head or in their

00:05:20.758 --> 00:05:23.389
idea.
He searched through world

00:05:23.389 --> 00:05:28.511
literature to try to find some
use of the term that preceded

00:05:28.511 --> 00:05:33.892
the 1600s and he concluded that
there were probably a number of

00:05:33.892 --> 00:05:39.261
people who had the idea,
but they didn't publish it,

00:05:39.261 --> 00:05:45.598
and it never became part of the
established literature partly

00:05:45.598 --> 00:05:48.806
because,
he said, throughout human

00:05:48.806 --> 00:05:53.474
history, there has been a love
of gambling and probability

00:05:53.474 --> 00:05:57.649
theory is extremely useful if
you are a gambler.

00:05:57.649 --> 00:06:02.713
Hacking believes that there
were many gambling theorists who

00:06:02.713 --> 00:06:07.690
invented probability theory at
various times in history but

00:06:07.690 --> 00:06:11.810
never wrote it down and kept it
as a secret.

00:06:11.810 --> 00:06:22.258
He gives an example--I like
to--he gives an example from a

00:06:22.258 --> 00:06:30.139
book that--or it's a
collection--I think,

00:06:30.139 --> 00:06:35.121
a collection of epic poems
written in Sanskrit that goes

00:06:35.121 --> 00:06:40.645
back--it was actually written
over a course of 1,000 years and

00:06:40.645 --> 00:06:44.540
it was completed in the fourth
century.

00:06:44.540 --> 00:06:50.517
Well, there's a story--there's
a long story in the Mahabarahta

00:06:50.517 --> 00:06:56.495
about an emperor called Nala and
he had a wife named Damayanti

00:06:56.495 --> 00:07:01.199
and he was a very pure and very
good person.

00:07:01.199 --> 00:07:07.849
There was an evil demon called
Kali who hated Nala and wanted

00:07:07.849 --> 00:07:13.722
to bring his downfall,
so he had to find a weakness of

00:07:13.722 --> 00:07:16.493
Nala.
He found finally some,

00:07:16.493 --> 00:07:21.008
even though Nala was so pure
and so perfect--he found one

00:07:21.008 --> 00:07:25.527
weakness and that was gambling.
Nala couldn't resist the

00:07:25.527 --> 00:07:30.226
opportunity to gamble;
so the evil demon seduced him

00:07:30.226 --> 00:07:34.700
into gambling aggressively.
You know sometimes when you're

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:37.809
losing and you redouble and you
keep hoping to win back what

00:07:37.809 --> 00:07:40.594
you've lost?
In a fit of gambling,

00:07:40.594 --> 00:07:45.817
Nala finally gambled his entire
kingdom and lost--it's a

00:07:45.817 --> 00:07:51.610
terrible story--and Nala then
had to leave the kingdom and his

00:07:51.610 --> 00:07:54.259
wife.
They wandered for years.

00:07:54.259 --> 00:07:57.009
He separated from her because
of dire necessity.

00:07:57.009 --> 00:08:00.688
They were wandering in the
forests and he was in despair,

00:08:00.688 --> 00:08:05.425
having lost everything.
But then he meets someone by

00:08:05.425 --> 00:08:10.620
the name of--we have Nala and he
meets this man,

00:08:10.620 --> 00:08:17.142
Rituparna, and this is where a
probability theory apparently

00:08:17.142 --> 00:08:21.152
comes in.
Rituparna tells Nala that he

00:08:21.152 --> 00:08:26.430
knows the science of gambling
and he will teach it to Nala,

00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:31.128
but that it has to be done by
whispering it in his ear because

00:08:31.128 --> 00:08:35.549
it's a deep and extreme secret.
Nala is skeptical.

00:08:35.549 --> 00:08:38.240
How does Rituparna know how to
gamble?

00:08:38.240 --> 00:08:43.274
So Rituparna tries to prove to
him his abilities and he says,

00:08:43.274 --> 00:08:47.220
see that tree there,
I can estimate how many leaves

00:08:47.220 --> 00:08:51.210
there are on that tree by
counting leaves on one branch.

00:08:51.210 --> 00:08:56.960
Rituparna looked at one branch
and estimated the number of

00:08:56.960 --> 00:09:01.500
leaves on the tree,
but Nala was skeptical.

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:06.297
He stayed up all night and
counted every leaf on the tree

00:09:06.297 --> 00:09:10.409
and it came very close to what
Rituparna said;

00:09:10.409 --> 00:09:18.320
so he--the next
morning--believed Rituparna.

00:09:18.320 --> 00:09:20.597
Now this is interesting,
Hacking says,

00:09:20.597 --> 00:09:23.982
because it shows that sampling
theory was part of Nala's

00:09:23.982 --> 00:09:26.482
theory.
You don't have to count all the

00:09:26.482 --> 00:09:29.303
leaves on the tree,
you can take a sample and you

00:09:29.303 --> 00:09:31.419
count that and then you
multiply.

00:09:31.419 --> 00:09:36.175
Anyway, the story ends and Nala
goes back and is now armed with

00:09:36.175 --> 00:09:38.629
probability theory,
we assume.

00:09:38.629 --> 00:09:42.387
He goes back and gambles again,
but he has nothing left to

00:09:42.387 --> 00:09:47.860
wager except his wife;
so he puts her and gambles her.

00:09:47.860 --> 00:09:50.389
But remember,
now he knows what he's doing

00:09:50.389 --> 00:09:54.214
and so he really wasn't gambling
his wife--he was really a very

00:09:54.214 --> 00:09:58.496
pure and honorable man.
So he won back the entire

00:09:58.496 --> 00:10:03.461
kingdom and that's the ending.
Anyway, that shows that I think

00:10:03.461 --> 00:10:05.960
probability theory does have a
long history,

00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:10.143
but--it not being an
intellectual discipline--it

00:10:10.143 --> 00:10:14.950
didn't really inform a
generation of finance theory.

00:10:14.950 --> 00:10:18.364
When you don't have a theory,
then you don't have a way to be

00:10:18.364 --> 00:10:21.840
rigorous.
So, it was in the 1600s that

00:10:21.840 --> 00:10:28.050
probability theory started to
get written down as a theory and

00:10:28.050 --> 00:10:33.139
many things then happened in
that century that,

00:10:33.139 --> 00:10:36.539
I think, are precursors both to
finance and insurance.

00:10:36.539 --> 00:10:41.272
One was in the 1600s when
people started constructing life

00:10:41.272 --> 00:10:43.360
tables.
What is a life table?

00:10:43.360 --> 00:10:47.779
It's a table showing the
probability of dying at each

00:10:47.779 --> 00:10:51.935
age, for each age and sex.
That's what you need to know if

00:10:51.935 --> 00:10:53.940
you're going to do life
insurance.

00:10:53.940 --> 00:10:57.543
So, they started to do
collecting of data on mortality

00:10:57.543 --> 00:11:01.350
and they developed something
called actuarial science,

00:11:01.350 --> 00:11:05.280
which is estimating the
probability of people living.

00:11:09.269 --> 00:11:15.429
That then became the basis for
insurance.

00:11:15.429 --> 00:11:20.549
Actually, insurance goes back
to ancient Rome in some form.

00:11:20.549 --> 00:11:23.903
In ancient Rome they had
something called burial

00:11:23.903 --> 00:11:27.361
insurance.
You could buy a policy that

00:11:27.361 --> 00:11:32.757
protected you against your
family not having the money to

00:11:32.757 --> 00:11:36.579
bury you if you died.
In ancient culture people

00:11:36.579 --> 00:11:39.476
worried a great deal about being
properly buried,

00:11:39.476 --> 00:11:41.649
so that's an interesting
concept.

00:11:41.649 --> 00:11:44.039
They were selling that in
ancient Rome;

00:11:44.039 --> 00:11:47.730
but you might think,
but why just for burial?

00:11:47.730 --> 00:11:50.710
Why don't you make it into
full-blown life insurance?

00:11:50.710 --> 00:11:52.580
You kind of wonder why they
didn't.

00:11:52.580 --> 00:11:55.870
I think maybe it's because they
didn't have the concepts down.

00:11:55.870 --> 00:11:59.789
In Renaissance Italy they
started writing insurance

00:11:59.789 --> 00:12:03.629
policies--I read one of the
insurance policies,

00:12:03.629 --> 00:12:07.410
it's in the Journal of Risk and
Insurance--and they translate a

00:12:07.410 --> 00:12:11.068
Renaissance insurance policy and
it's very hard to understand

00:12:11.068 --> 00:12:15.092
what this policy was saying.
I guess they didn't have our

00:12:15.092 --> 00:12:19.607
language, they didn't--they were
intuitively halfway there but

00:12:19.607 --> 00:12:23.720
they couldn't express it,
so I think the industry didn't

00:12:23.720 --> 00:12:27.119
get really started.
I think it was the invention of

00:12:27.119 --> 00:12:30.869
probability theory that really
started it and that's why I

00:12:30.869 --> 00:12:33.830
think theory is very important
in finance.

00:12:38.009 --> 00:12:42.929
Some people date fire insurance
with the fire of London in 1666.

00:12:42.929 --> 00:12:45.947
The whole city burned down,
practically,

00:12:45.947 --> 00:12:50.511
in a terrible fire and fire
insurance started to proliferate

00:12:50.511 --> 00:12:53.644
right after that in London.
But you know,

00:12:53.644 --> 00:12:57.090
you kind of wonder if that's a
good example for fire insurance

00:12:57.090 --> 00:12:59.350
because if the whole city burns
down,

00:12:59.350 --> 00:13:01.782
then insurance companies would
go bankrupt anyway,

00:13:01.782 --> 00:13:03.719
right?
London insurance companies

00:13:03.719 --> 00:13:07.093
would because the whole concept
of insurance is pooling of

00:13:07.093 --> 00:13:08.810
independent probabilities.

00:13:12.230 --> 00:13:14.700
Nonetheless,
that was the beginning.

00:13:14.700 --> 00:13:20.042
We're also going to recognize,
however, that insurance got a

00:13:20.042 --> 00:13:25.476
slow start because--I believe it
is because--people could not

00:13:25.476 --> 00:13:29.279
understand the concept of
probability.

00:13:29.279 --> 00:13:35.020
They didn't have the concept
firmly in mind.

00:13:35.020 --> 00:13:38.592
There are lots of aspects to it.
In order to understand

00:13:38.592 --> 00:13:43.747
probability, you have to take
things as coming from a random

00:13:43.747 --> 00:13:49.078
event and people don't clearly
have that in their mind from an

00:13:49.078 --> 00:13:53.443
intuitive standpoint.
They have maybe a sense that I

00:13:53.443 --> 00:13:57.350
can influence events by willing
or wishing and if I think

00:13:57.350 --> 00:14:00.769
that--if I have kind of a
mystical side to me,

00:14:00.769 --> 00:14:04.700
then probabilities don't have a
clear meaning.

00:14:04.700 --> 00:14:10.730
It has been shown that even
today people seem to think that.

00:14:10.730 --> 00:14:16.835
They don't really take,
at an intuitive level,

00:14:16.835 --> 00:14:21.397
probabilities as objective.
For example,

00:14:21.397 --> 00:14:24.480
if you ask people how much they
would be willing to bet on a

00:14:24.480 --> 00:14:27.404
coin toss,
they will typically bet more if

00:14:27.404 --> 00:14:31.894
they can toss the coin or they
will bet more if the coin hasn't

00:14:31.894 --> 00:14:34.797
been tossed yet.
It could have been already

00:14:34.797 --> 00:14:37.919
tossed and concealed.
Why would that be?

00:14:37.919 --> 00:14:43.436
It might be that there's just
some intuitive sense that I

00:14:43.436 --> 00:14:49.346
can--I don't know--I have some
magical forces in me and I can

00:14:49.346 --> 00:14:52.966
change things.
The idea of probability theory

00:14:52.966 --> 00:14:56.350
is that no, you can't change
things, there are all these

00:14:56.350 --> 00:15:00.350
objective laws of probability
out there that guide everything.

00:15:00.350 --> 00:15:10.378
Most languages around the world
have a different word for luck

00:15:10.378 --> 00:15:17.779
and risk--or luck and fortune.
Luck seems to mean something

00:15:17.779 --> 00:15:20.529
about you: like I'm a lucky
person.

00:15:20.529 --> 00:15:23.494
I don't know what that
means--like God or the gods

00:15:23.494 --> 00:15:26.639
favor me and so I'm lucky or
this is my lucky day.

00:15:26.639 --> 00:15:31.220
Probability theory is really a
movement away from that.

00:15:31.220 --> 00:15:38.659
We then have a mathematically
rigorous discipline.

00:15:38.659 --> 00:15:45.487
Now, I'm going to go through
some of the terms of probability

00:15:45.487 --> 00:15:50.379
and--this will be review for
many of you,

00:15:50.379 --> 00:15:56.012
but it will be something that
we're going to use in the--So

00:15:56.012 --> 00:16:02.033
I'll use the symbol P or
I can sometimes write it out as

00:16:02.033 --> 00:16:06.210
prob to represent a
probability.

00:16:06.210 --> 00:16:11.977
It is always a number that lies
between zero and one,

00:16:11.977 --> 00:16:17.873
or between 0% and 100%.
"Percent" means divided by 100

00:16:17.873 --> 00:16:24.610
in Latin, so 100% is one.
If the probability is zero that

00:16:24.610 --> 00:16:30.407
means the event can't happen.
If the probability is one,

00:16:30.407 --> 00:16:33.179
it means that it's certain to
happen.

00:16:33.179 --> 00:16:36.220
If the probability is--Can
everyone see this from over

00:16:36.220 --> 00:16:39.995
there?
I can probably move this or

00:16:39.995 --> 00:16:41.980
can't I?
Yes, I can.

00:16:41.980 --> 00:16:46.300
Now, can you now--you're the
most disadvantaged person and

00:16:46.300 --> 00:16:48.120
you can see it,
right?

00:16:48.120 --> 00:16:58.900
So that's the basic idea.
One of the first principles of

00:16:58.900 --> 00:17:01.320
probability is the idea of
independence.

00:17:08.339 --> 00:17:17.583
The idea is that probability
measures the likelihood of some

00:17:17.583 --> 00:17:20.751
outcome.
Let's say the outcome of an

00:17:20.751 --> 00:17:24.488
experiment, like tossing a coin.
You might say the probability

00:17:24.488 --> 00:17:27.678
that you toss a coin and it
comes up heads is a half,

00:17:27.678 --> 00:17:30.930
because it's equally likely to
be heads and tails.

00:17:30.930 --> 00:17:36.282
Independent experiments are
experiments that occur without

00:17:36.282 --> 00:17:40.553
relation to each other.
If you toss a coin twice and

00:17:40.553 --> 00:17:43.920
the first experiment doesn't
influence the second,

00:17:43.920 --> 00:17:48.111
we say they're independent and
there's no relation between the

00:17:48.111 --> 00:17:51.180
two.
One of the first principles of

00:17:51.180 --> 00:17:55.590
probability theory is called the
multiplication rule.

00:18:00.569 --> 00:18:03.735
That says that if you have
independent probabilities,

00:18:03.735 --> 00:18:07.206
then the probability of two
events is equal to the product

00:18:07.206 --> 00:18:14.626
of their probabilities.
So, the Prob(A and

00:18:14.626 --> 00:18:22.020
B) = Prob(A)*Prob(B).

00:18:28.309 --> 00:18:32.869
That wouldn't hold if
they're not independent.

00:18:32.869 --> 00:18:38.081
The theory of insurance is that
ideally an insurance company

00:18:38.081 --> 00:18:41.349
wants to insure independent
events.

00:18:41.349 --> 00:18:44.464
Ideally, life insurance is
insuring people--or fire

00:18:44.464 --> 00:18:47.454
insurance is insuring
people--against independent

00:18:47.454 --> 00:18:50.380
events;
so it's not the fire of London.

00:18:50.380 --> 00:18:55.516
It's the problem that sometimes
people knock over an oil lamp in

00:18:55.516 --> 00:18:59.430
their home and they burn their
own house down.

00:18:59.430 --> 00:19:02.391
It's not going to burn any
other houses down since it's

00:19:02.391 --> 00:19:04.970
just completely independent of
anything else.

00:19:04.970 --> 00:19:08.722
So, the probability that the
whole city burns down is

00:19:08.722 --> 00:19:10.960
infinitesimally small,
right?

00:19:10.960 --> 00:19:13.574
This will generalize to
probability of A and

00:19:13.574 --> 00:19:16.765
B and C equals the
probability of A times

00:19:16.765 --> 00:19:19.432
the probability of B
times the probability of

00:19:19.432 --> 00:19:22.529
C and so on.
If the probability is 1 in

00:19:22.529 --> 00:19:26.519
1,000 that a house burns down
and there are 1,000 houses,

00:19:26.519 --> 00:19:31.912
then the probability that they
all burn down is 1/1000 to the

00:19:31.912 --> 00:19:34.799
1000th power,
which is virtually zero.

00:19:34.799 --> 00:19:37.635
So insurance companies
then–Basically,

00:19:37.635 --> 00:19:40.669
if they write a lot of
policies, then they have

00:19:40.669 --> 00:19:45.164
virtually no risk.
That is the fundamental idea

00:19:45.164 --> 00:19:52.015
that may seem simple and obvious
to you, but it certainly wasn't

00:19:52.015 --> 00:19:55.930
back when the idea first came
up.

