00:20:24.019 --> 00:20:27.616
If you follow through from the
independent theory,

00:20:27.616 --> 00:20:31.139
there's one of the basic
relations in probability

00:20:31.139 --> 00:20:34.809
theory--it's called the binomial
distribution.

00:20:34.809 --> 00:20:42.880
I'm not going to spend a whole
lot of time on this but it gives

00:20:42.880 --> 00:20:50.950
the probability of x
successes in n trials or,

00:20:50.950 --> 00:20:54.579
in the case of insurance
x, if you're insuring

00:20:54.579 --> 00:20:57.720
against an accident,
then the probability that

00:20:57.720 --> 00:21:01.490
you'll get x accidents
and n trials.

00:21:01.490 --> 00:21:12.414
The binomial distribution gives
the probability as a function of

00:21:12.414 --> 00:21:22.645
x and it's given by the
formula where P is the

00:21:22.645 --> 00:21:33.569
probability of the accident:
P^(X) (1-P)^(N-X) [n!/(n-x)!].

00:21:33.569 --> 00:21:37.990
That is the formula that
insurance companies use when

00:21:37.990 --> 00:21:41.220
they have independent
probabilities,

00:21:41.220 --> 00:21:47.228
to estimate the likelihood of
having a certain number of

00:21:47.228 --> 00:21:50.484
accidents.
They're concerned with having

00:21:50.484 --> 00:21:53.435
too many accidents,
which might exhaust their

00:21:53.435 --> 00:21:55.924
reserves.
An insurance company has

00:21:55.924 --> 00:21:59.714
reserves and it has enough
reserves to cover them for a

00:21:59.714 --> 00:22:03.598
certain number of accidents.
It uses the binomial

00:22:03.598 --> 00:22:08.296
distribution to calculate the
probability of getting any

00:22:08.296 --> 00:22:14.560
specific number of accidents.
So, that is the binomial

00:22:14.560 --> 00:22:16.620
distribution.

