00:22:40.460 --> 00:22:43.980
Another important concept in
probability theory that we will

00:22:43.980 --> 00:22:45.770
use a lot is expected value,

00:22:51.170 --> 00:22:56.448
the mean, or average--those are
all roughly interchangeable

00:22:56.448 --> 00:23:02.372
concepts.
We have expected value,

00:23:02.372 --> 00:23:06.010
mean or average.

00:23:14.369 --> 00:23:18.512
We can define it in a couple of
different ways depending on

00:23:18.512 --> 00:23:22.869
whether we're talking about
sample mean or population mean.

00:23:22.869 --> 00:23:28.198
The basic definition--the
expected value of some random

00:23:28.198 --> 00:23:34.512
variable x--E(x)--I guess
I should have said that a random

00:23:34.512 --> 00:23:39.150
variable is a quantity that
takes on value.

00:23:39.150 --> 00:23:43.471
If you have an experiment and
the outcome of the experiment is

00:23:43.471 --> 00:23:47.793
a number, then a random variable
is the number that comes from

00:23:47.793 --> 00:23:49.980
the experiment.
For example,

00:23:49.980 --> 00:23:52.779
the experiment could be tossing
a coin;

00:23:52.779 --> 00:23:56.556
I will call the outcome
heads the number one,

00:23:56.556 --> 00:24:00.555
and I'll call the outcome
tails the number zero,

00:24:00.555 --> 00:24:03.740
so I've just defined a random
variable.

00:24:03.740 --> 00:24:07.245
You have discrete random
variables, like the one I just

00:24:07.245 --> 00:24:10.296
defined, or there are
also--which take on only a

00:24:10.296 --> 00:24:14.385
finite number of values--and we
have continuous random variables

00:24:14.385 --> 00:24:18.410
that can take on any number of
values along a continuum.

00:24:18.410 --> 00:24:22.372
Another experiment would be to
mix two chemicals together and

00:24:22.372 --> 00:24:25.740
put a thermometer in and measure
the temperature.

00:24:25.740 --> 00:24:28.848
That's another invention of the
1600s, by the way--the

00:24:28.848 --> 00:24:31.152
thermometer.
And they learned that

00:24:31.152 --> 00:24:34.470
concept--perfectly natural to
us--temperature.

00:24:34.470 --> 00:24:37.339
But it was a new idea in the
1600s.

00:24:37.339 --> 00:24:39.940
So anyway, that's continuous,
right?

00:24:39.940 --> 00:24:42.892
When you mix two chemicals
together, it could be any

00:24:42.892 --> 00:24:46.191
number, there's an infinite
number of possible numbers and

00:24:46.191 --> 00:24:50.741
that would be continuous.
For discrete random variables,

00:24:50.741 --> 00:24:56.004
we can define the expected
value, or µ_x

00:24:56.004 --> 00:25:01.364
--that's the Greek letter
mu--as the summation i =

00:25:01.364 --> 00:25:08.993
1 to infinity of.
[P(x=x_i) times

00:25:08.993 --> 00:25:15.066
(x_i)].
I have it down that there might

00:25:15.066 --> 00:25:18.719
be an infinite number of
possible values for the random

00:25:18.719 --> 00:25:21.766
variable x.
In the case of the coin toss,

00:25:21.766 --> 00:25:24.571
there are only two,
but I'm saying in general there

00:25:24.571 --> 00:25:28.151
could be an infinite number.
But they're accountable and we

00:25:28.151 --> 00:25:31.833
can list all possible values
when they're discrete and form a

00:25:31.833 --> 00:25:34.779
probability weighted average of
the outcomes.

00:25:34.779 --> 00:25:36.670
That's called the expected
value.

00:25:36.670 --> 00:25:40.490
People also call that the mean
or the average.

00:25:40.490 --> 00:25:45.680
But, note that this is based on
theory.

00:25:45.680 --> 00:25:50.469
These are probabilities.
In order to compute using this

00:25:50.469 --> 00:25:55.450
formula you have to know the
true probabilities.

00:25:55.450 --> 00:26:00.060
There's another formula that
applies for a continuous random

00:26:00.060 --> 00:26:04.904
variables and it's the same idea
except that--I'll also call it

00:26:04.904 --> 00:26:09.410
µ_x,
except that it's an integral.

00:26:09.410 --> 00:26:17.942
We have the integral from minus
infinity to plus infinity of

00:26:17.942 --> 00:26:22.579
F(x)*x*dx,
and that's really--you see it's

00:26:22.579 --> 00:26:25.687
the same thing because an
integral is analogous to a

00:26:25.687 --> 00:26:26.480
summation.

00:26:32.019 --> 00:26:35.319
Those are the two population
definitions.

00:26:35.319 --> 00:26:40.148
F(x) is the continuous
probability distribution for

00:26:40.148 --> 00:26:41.080
x.

00:26:45.589 --> 00:26:49.211
That's different when you have
continuous values--you don't

00:26:49.211 --> 00:26:52.021
have P (x =
x_i) because it's

00:26:52.021 --> 00:26:54.832
always zero.
The probability that the

00:26:54.832 --> 00:26:59.287
temperature is exactly 100°
is zero because it could be

00:26:59.287 --> 00:27:02.534
100.0001°
or something else and there's

00:27:02.534 --> 00:27:05.630
an infinite number of
possibilities.

00:27:05.630 --> 00:27:10.663
We have instead what's called a
probability density when we have

00:27:10.663 --> 00:27:14.675
continuous random variables.
You're not going to need to

00:27:14.675 --> 00:27:18.384
know a lot about this for this
course, but this is--I wanted to

00:27:18.384 --> 00:27:22.686
get the basic ideas down.
These are called population

00:27:22.686 --> 00:27:28.717
measures because they refer to
the whole population of possible

00:27:28.717 --> 00:27:33.289
outcomes and they measure the
probabilities.

00:27:33.289 --> 00:27:38.231
It's the truth,
but there are also sample

00:27:38.231 --> 00:27:40.931
means.
When you get--this is

00:27:40.931 --> 00:27:45.657
Rituparna, counting the leaves
on a tree--you can estimate,

00:27:45.657 --> 00:27:49.650
from a sample,
the population expected values.

00:27:49.650 --> 00:27:56.720
The population mean is often
written "x-bar."

00:27:56.720 --> 00:28:00.787
If you have a sample with
n observations,

00:28:00.787 --> 00:28:04.682
it's the summation i = 1
to n of

00:28:04.682 --> 00:28:08.750
x_i/n--that's
the average.

00:28:08.750 --> 00:28:12.333
You know that formula, right?
You count n leaves--you

00:28:12.333 --> 00:28:17.813
count the number of leaves.
You have n branches on

00:28:17.813 --> 00:28:24.590
the tree and you count the
number of leaves and sum them

00:28:24.590 --> 00:28:27.320
up.
One would be--I'm having a

00:28:27.320 --> 00:28:31.302
little trouble putting this into
the Rituparna story,

00:28:31.302 --> 00:28:34.559
but you see the idea.
You know the average, I assume.

00:28:34.559 --> 00:28:40.046
That's the most elementary
concept and you could use it to

00:28:40.046 --> 00:28:45.630
estimate either a discreet or
continuous expected value.

00:28:45.630 --> 00:28:49.869
In finance, there's often
reference to another kind of

00:28:49.869 --> 00:28:53.869
average, which I want to refer
you to and which,

00:28:53.869 --> 00:28:58.049
in the Jeremy Siegel book,
a lot is made of this.

00:28:58.049 --> 00:29:05.279
The other kind of average is
called the geometric average.

00:29:05.279 --> 00:29:16.142
We'll call that--I'll only show
the sample version of it G(x) =

00:29:16.142 --> 00:29:25.427
the product i = 1 to
n of (x_i

00:29:25.427 --> 00:29:29.010
)^(1/n).
Does everyone--Can you see that?

00:29:35.170 --> 00:29:38.676
Instead of summing them and
dividing by M,

00:29:38.676 --> 00:29:43.380
I multiply them all together
and take the n^(th) root of

00:29:43.380 --> 00:29:46.942
them.
This is called the geometric

00:29:46.942 --> 00:29:51.829
average and it's used only for
positive numbers.

00:29:51.829 --> 00:29:54.776
So, if you have any negative
numbers you'd have a problem,

00:29:54.776 --> 00:29:56.473
right?
If you had one negative number

00:29:56.473 --> 00:29:58.869
in it, then the product would be
a negative number and,

00:29:58.869 --> 00:30:01.969
if you took a root of that,
then you might get an imaginary

00:30:01.969 --> 00:30:06.128
number.
We don't want to use it in that

00:30:06.128 --> 00:30:09.101
case.
There's an appendix to one of

00:30:09.101 --> 00:30:13.859
the chapters in Jeremy Siegel's
book where he says that one of

00:30:13.859 --> 00:30:18.772
the most important applications
of this theory is to measure how

00:30:18.772 --> 00:30:21.190
successful an investor is.

00:30:26.119 --> 00:30:30.030
Suppose someone is managing
money.

00:30:30.030 --> 00:30:34.853
Have they done well?
If so, you would say,

00:30:34.853 --> 00:30:37.795
"Well, they've been investing
money over a number of different

00:30:37.795 --> 00:30:39.809
years.
Let's take the average over all

00:30:39.809 --> 00:30:42.498
the different years."
Suppose someone has been

00:30:42.498 --> 00:30:46.287
investing money for n
years and x_i

00:30:46.287 --> 00:30:49.619
is the return on the investment
in a given year.

00:30:49.619 --> 00:30:51.440
What is their average
performance?

00:30:51.440 --> 00:30:54.180
The natural thing to do would
be to average them up,

00:30:54.180 --> 00:30:57.767
right?
But Jeremy says that maybe

00:30:57.767 --> 00:31:02.140
that's not a very good thing to
do.

00:31:02.140 --> 00:31:08.758
What he says you should do
instead is to take the geometric

00:31:08.758 --> 00:31:14.782
average of gross returns.
The return on an investment is

00:31:14.782 --> 00:31:20.274
how much you made from the
investment as a percent of the

00:31:20.274 --> 00:31:26.022
money invested.
The gross return is the return

00:31:26.022 --> 00:31:29.263
plus one.
The worst you can ever do

00:31:29.263 --> 00:31:33.319
investing is lose all of your
investment--lose 100%.

00:31:33.319 --> 00:31:38.350
If we add one to the return,
then you've got a number that's

00:31:38.350 --> 00:31:43.039
never negative and we can then
use geometric returns.

00:31:43.039 --> 00:31:47.375
Jeremy Siegel says that in
finance we should be using

00:31:47.375 --> 00:31:50.710
geometric and not arithmetic
averages.

00:31:50.710 --> 00:31:52.583
Why is that?
Well I'll tell you in very

00:31:52.583 --> 00:31:53.640
simple terms,
I think.

00:31:53.640 --> 00:31:57.572
Suppose someone is investing
your money and he announces,

00:31:57.572 --> 00:32:01.451
I have had very good returns.
I have invested and I've

00:32:01.451 --> 00:32:05.420
produced 20% a year for nine out
of the last ten years.

00:32:05.420 --> 00:32:09.670
You think that's great,
but what about the last year.

00:32:09.670 --> 00:32:13.630
The guy says,
"Oh I lost 100% in that year."

00:32:13.630 --> 00:32:16.480
You might say,
"Alright, that's good."

00:32:16.480 --> 00:32:21.130
I would add up 20% a year for
nine years and than put in a

00:32:21.130 --> 00:32:24.638
zero–no,
120 because it's gross return

00:32:24.638 --> 00:32:28.799
for nine years--and put in a
zero for one year.

00:32:28.799 --> 00:32:31.319
Maybe that doesn't look bad,
right?

00:32:31.319 --> 00:32:33.892
But think about it,
if you were investing your

00:32:33.892 --> 00:32:37.150
money with someone like that,
what did you end up with?

00:32:37.150 --> 00:32:40.844
You ended up with nothing.
If they have one year when they

00:32:40.844 --> 00:32:43.185
lose everything,
it doesn't matter how much they

00:32:43.185 --> 00:32:46.891
made in the other years.
Jeremy says in the text that

00:32:46.891 --> 00:32:52.120
the geometric return is always
lower than the arithmetic return

00:32:52.120 --> 00:32:55.410
unless all the numbers are the
same.

00:32:55.410 --> 00:33:02.480
It's a less optimistic version.
So, we should use that,

00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:06.510
but people in finance resist
using that because it's a lower

00:33:06.510 --> 00:33:10.198
number and when you're
advertising your return you want

00:33:10.198 --> 00:33:12.930
to make it look as big as
possible.

00:33:12.930 --> 00:33:17.063
We also need some measure
of--We've been talking here

00:33:17.063 --> 00:33:21.514
about measures of central
tendency only and in finance we

00:33:21.514 --> 00:33:24.659
need,
as well, measures of

00:33:24.659 --> 00:33:30.490
dispersion, which is how much
something varies.

00:33:30.490 --> 00:33:35.252
Central tendency is a measure
of the center of a probability

00:33:35.252 --> 00:33:40.015
distribution of the--Central
tendency is a measure--Variance

00:33:40.015 --> 00:33:44.939
is a measure of how much things
change from one observation to

00:33:44.939 --> 00:33:49.795
another.
We have variance and it's often

00:33:49.795 --> 00:33:56.765
represented by σ²,
that's the Greek letter sigma,

00:33:56.765 --> 00:34:03.780
lower case, squared.
Or, especially when talking

00:34:03.780 --> 00:34:12.596
about estimates of the variance,
we sometimes say S²

00:34:12.596 --> 00:34:19.679
or we say standard
deviation².

00:34:19.679 --> 00:34:22.909
The standard deviation is the
square root of the variance.

00:34:22.909 --> 00:34:31.828
For population variance,
the variance of some random

00:34:31.828 --> 00:34:42.671
variable x is defined as
the summation i = 1 to infinity

00:34:42.671 --> 00:34:50.716
of the Prob (x =
x_i) times

00:34:50.716 --> 00:34:59.809
(x_i -
µ_x)^(2).

00:34:59.809 --> 00:35:05.827
So mu is the mean--we just
defined it of x--that's

00:35:05.827 --> 00:35:11.199
the expectation of x or
also E(x),

00:35:11.199 --> 00:35:15.606
so it's the probability
weighted average of the squared

00:35:15.606 --> 00:35:19.718
deviations from the mean.
If it moves a lot--either way

00:35:19.718 --> 00:35:23.469
from the mean--then this number
squared is a big number.

00:35:23.469 --> 00:35:28.269
The more x moves,
the bigger the variance is.

00:35:28.269 --> 00:35:35.370
There's also another variance
measure, which we use in the

00:35:35.370 --> 00:35:41.474
sample--or also Var is used
sometimes--and this is

00:35:41.474 --> 00:35:46.526
∑².
There's also another variance

00:35:46.526 --> 00:35:49.090
measure, which is for the
sample.

00:35:49.090 --> 00:35:56.935
When we have n
observations it's just the

00:35:56.935 --> 00:36:06.950
summation i = 1 to n of
(x - x bar)²/n.

00:36:12.870 --> 00:36:18.824
That is the sample variance.
Some people will divide by

00:36:18.824 --> 00:36:24.387
n–1.
I suppose I would accept either

00:36:24.387 --> 00:36:27.869
answer.
I'm just keeping it simple here.

00:36:27.869 --> 00:36:34.400
They divide by n-1 to
make it an unbiased estimator of

00:36:34.400 --> 00:36:38.896
the population variance;
but I'm just going to show it

00:36:38.896 --> 00:36:41.875
in a simple way here.
So you see what it is--it's a

00:36:41.875 --> 00:36:45.010
measure of how much x
deviates from the mean;

00:36:45.010 --> 00:36:48.456
but it's squared.
It weights big deviations a lot

00:36:48.456 --> 00:36:51.450
because the square of a big
number is really big.

00:36:51.450 --> 00:37:00.285
So, that's the variance.
So, that completes central

00:37:00.285 --> 00:37:04.829
tendency and dispersion.
We're going to be talking about

00:37:04.829 --> 00:37:08.776
these in finance in regards to
returns because--generally the

00:37:08.776 --> 00:37:11.539
idea here is that we want high
returns.

00:37:11.539 --> 00:37:15.877
We want a high expected value
of returns, but we don't like

00:37:15.877 --> 00:37:18.973
variance.
Expected value is good and

00:37:18.973 --> 00:37:22.210
variance is bad because that's
risk;

00:37:22.210 --> 00:37:25.421
that's uncertainty.
That's what this whole theory

00:37:25.421 --> 00:37:30.368
is about: how to get a lot of
expected return without getting

00:37:30.368 --> 00:37:33.884
a lot of risk.
Another concept that's very

00:37:33.884 --> 00:37:38.887
basic here is covariance.
Covariance is a measure of how

00:37:38.887 --> 00:37:42.250
much two variables move
together.

00:37:42.250 --> 00:37:53.479
Covariance is--we'll call
it--now we have two random

00:37:53.479 --> 00:38:06.030
variables, so I'll just talk
about it in a sample term.

00:38:06.030 --> 00:38:15.523
It's the summation i = 1
to n of [(x –

00:38:15.523 --> 00:38:22.960
x-bar) times (y –
y-bar)]/n.

00:38:22.960 --> 00:38:28.769
So x is the deviation
for the i-subscript,

00:38:28.769 --> 00:38:34.050
meaning we have a separate
x_i and

00:38:34.050 --> 00:38:38.170
y_i for each
observation.

00:38:38.170 --> 00:38:41.002
So we're talking about an
experiment when you

00:38:41.002 --> 00:38:44.671
generate--Each experiment
generates both an x and a

00:38:44.671 --> 00:38:48.469
y observation and we know
when x is high,

00:38:48.469 --> 00:38:51.696
y also tends to be high,
or whether it's the other way

00:38:51.696 --> 00:38:54.400
around.
If they tend to move together,

00:38:54.400 --> 00:38:58.617
when x is high and
y is high together at the

00:38:58.617 --> 00:39:01.556
same time,
then the covariance will tend

00:39:01.556 --> 00:39:04.966
to be a positive number.
If when x is low,

00:39:04.966 --> 00:39:08.947
y also tends to be low,
then this will be negative

00:39:08.947 --> 00:39:13.000
number and so will this,
so their product is positive.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:18.260
A positive covariance means
that the two move together.

00:39:18.260 --> 00:39:21.715
A negative covariance means
that they tend to move opposite

00:39:21.715 --> 00:39:24.216
each other.
If x is high relative to

00:39:24.216 --> 00:39:27.169
x-bar--this is
positive--then y tends to

00:39:27.169 --> 00:39:30.010
be low relative to its mean
y-bar and this is

00:39:30.010 --> 00:39:31.933
negative.
So the product would be

00:39:31.933 --> 00:39:34.083
negative.
If you get a lot of negative

00:39:34.083 --> 00:39:36.800
products, that makes the
covariance negative.

00:39:36.800 --> 00:39:41.410
Then I want to move to
correlation.

00:39:47.090 --> 00:39:51.800
So this is a measure--it's a
scaled covariance.

00:39:51.800 --> 00:39:56.980
We tend to use the Greek letter
rho.

00:39:56.980 --> 00:40:01.424
If you were to use Excel,
it would be correl or

00:40:01.424 --> 00:40:05.000
sometimes I say corr.
That's the correlation.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:12.760
This number always lies between
-1 and +1.

00:40:19.469 --> 00:40:26.143
It is defined as rho=
[cov(x_iy

00:40:26.143 --> 00:40:32.983
_i)/S_x
S_y]

00:40:32.983 --> 00:40:39.489
That's the correlation
coefficient.

00:40:39.489 --> 00:40:43.540
That has kind of almost entered
the English language in the

00:40:43.540 --> 00:40:47.800
sense that you'll see it quoted
occasionally in newspapers.

00:40:47.800 --> 00:40:51.509
I don't know how much you're
used to it--Where would you see

00:40:51.509 --> 00:40:53.999
that?
They would say there is a low

00:40:53.999 --> 00:40:58.029
correlation between SAT scores
and grade point averages in

00:40:58.029 --> 00:41:01.210
college, or maybe it's a high
correlation.

00:41:01.210 --> 00:41:04.579
Does anyone know what it is?
But you could estimate the

00:41:04.579 --> 00:41:09.195
corr--it's probably positive.
I bet it's way below one,

00:41:09.195 --> 00:41:14.469
but it has some correlation,
so maybe it's .3.

00:41:14.469 --> 00:41:19.366
That would mean that people who
have high SAT scores tend to get

00:41:19.366 --> 00:41:22.202
higher grades.
If it were negative--it's very

00:41:22.202 --> 00:41:25.070
unlikely that it's negative--it
couldn't be negative.

00:41:25.070 --> 00:41:29.076
It couldn't be that people who
have high SAT scores tend to do

00:41:29.076 --> 00:41:32.630
poorly in college.
If you quantify how much they

00:41:32.630 --> 00:41:36.340
relate, then you could look at
the correlation.

00:41:42.580 --> 00:41:50.096
I want to move to regression.
This is another concept that is

00:41:50.096 --> 00:41:55.663
very basic to statistics,
but it has particular use in

00:41:55.663 --> 00:42:00.809
finance, so I'll give you a
financial example.

00:42:00.809 --> 00:42:07.755
The concept of regression goes
back to the mathematician Gauss,

00:42:07.755 --> 00:42:14.699
who talked about fitting a line
through a scatter of points.

00:42:14.699 --> 00:42:22.309
Let's draw a line through a
scatter of points here.

00:42:22.309 --> 00:42:31.269
I want to put down on this axis
the return on the stock market

00:42:31.269 --> 00:42:39.494
and on this axis I want to put
the return on one company,

00:42:39.494 --> 00:42:43.020
let's say Microsoft.

00:42:46.690 --> 00:42:49.989
I'm going to have each
observation as a year.

00:42:49.989 --> 00:42:53.313
I shouldn't put down a name of
a company because I can't

00:42:53.313 --> 00:42:55.670
reproduce this diagram for
Microsoft.

00:42:55.670 --> 00:43:02.494
Let's not say Microsoft,
let's say Shiller,

00:43:02.494 --> 00:43:04.701
Inc.
There's no such company,

00:43:04.701 --> 00:43:06.599
so I can be completely
hypothetical.

00:43:06.599 --> 00:43:11.844
Let's put zero here because
these are not gross returns

00:43:11.844 --> 00:43:16.409
these are returns,
so they're often negative.

00:43:16.409 --> 00:43:20.865
Suppose that in a given
year--and say this is minus five

00:43:20.865 --> 00:43:25.330
and this is plus five,
this is minus five and this is

00:43:25.330 --> 00:43:30.120
plus five--Suppose that in the
first year in our sample,

00:43:30.120 --> 00:43:36.139
the company Shiller, Inc.
and the market both did 5%.

00:43:36.139 --> 00:43:44.070
That puts a point right there
at five and five.

00:43:44.070 --> 00:43:48.900
In another year,
however, the stock market lost

00:43:48.900 --> 00:43:51.210
5% and Shiller,
Inc.

00:43:51.210 --> 00:43:55.313
lost 7%.
We would have a point,

00:43:55.313 --> 00:43:59.059
say, down here at five and
seven.

00:43:59.059 --> 00:44:02.978
This could be 1979,
this could be 1980,

00:44:02.978 --> 00:44:09.679
and we keep adding points so we
have a whole scatter of points.

00:44:09.679 --> 00:44:14.409
It's probably upward sloping,
right?

00:44:14.409 --> 00:44:19.469
Probably when the overall stock
market does well so does

00:44:19.469 --> 00:44:22.585
Shiller, Inc.
What Gauss did was said,

00:44:22.585 --> 00:44:26.127
let's fit a line through the
point--the scatter of

00:44:26.127 --> 00:44:29.670
points--and that's called the
regression line.

00:44:29.670 --> 00:44:35.877
He chose the line so that--this
is Gauss--he chose the line to

00:44:35.877 --> 00:44:41.882
minimize the sum of squared
distances of the points from the

00:44:41.882 --> 00:44:44.240
lines.
So these distances are the

00:44:44.240 --> 00:44:47.749
lengths of these line segments.
To get the best fitting line,

00:44:47.749 --> 00:44:50.956
you find the line that
minimizes the sum of squared

00:44:50.956 --> 00:44:53.816
distances.
That's called the regression

00:44:53.816 --> 00:44:57.652
line and the intercept is called
alpha--there's

00:44:57.652 --> 00:45:00.445
alpha.
And the slope is called

00:45:00.445 --> 00:45:04.818
beta.
That may be a familiar enough

00:45:04.818 --> 00:45:10.049
concept to you,
but in the context of finance

00:45:10.049 --> 00:45:15.811
this is a major concept.
The way I've written it,

00:45:15.811 --> 00:45:19.320
the beta of Shiller,
Inc.

00:45:19.320 --> 00:45:25.511
is the slope of this line.
The alpha is just the

00:45:25.511 --> 00:45:29.200
intercept of this curve.

00:45:33.170 --> 00:45:35.409
We can also do this with excess
returns.

00:45:35.409 --> 00:45:38.790
I will get to this later,
where I have the return minus

00:45:38.790 --> 00:45:42.609
the interest rate on this axis
and the market return minus the

00:45:42.609 --> 00:45:45.976
interest rate on this axis.
In that case,

00:45:45.976 --> 00:45:50.915
alpha is a measure of
how much Shiller,

00:45:50.915 --> 00:45:53.110
Inc.
outperforms.

00:45:53.110 --> 00:45:56.223
We'll come back to this,
but beta of the stock is

00:45:56.223 --> 00:45:59.223
a measure of how much it moves
with the market and the

00:45:59.223 --> 00:46:02.960
alpha of a stock is how
much it outperforms the market.

00:46:02.960 --> 00:46:05.680
We'll have to come back to
that--these are basic concepts.

00:46:12.860 --> 00:46:18.166
I want to--another concept--I
guess I've just been implicit in

00:46:18.166 --> 00:46:22.690
what I have--There's a
distribution called the normal

00:46:22.690 --> 00:46:27.910
distribution and that is--I'm
sure you've heard of this,

00:46:27.910 --> 00:46:33.059
right?
If you have a distribution that

00:46:33.059 --> 00:46:39.478
looks like this--it's
bell-shaped--this is x

00:46:39.478 --> 00:46:46.539
and--I have to make it look
symmetric which I may not be

00:46:46.539 --> 00:46:52.060
able to do that well--this is
f(x),

00:46:52.060 --> 00:46:56.783
 the normal distribution.
f(x) = [1/(√

00:46:56.783 --> 00:47:01.979
(2π)σ)]
times e to minus

00:47:01.979 --> 00:47:09.103
[(x-µ)^(2) / 2σ].
It's a famous formula,

00:47:09.103 --> 00:47:14.405
which is due to Gauss again.
We often assume in finance that

00:47:14.405 --> 00:47:16.901
random variables,
such as returns,

00:47:16.901 --> 00:47:21.485
are normally distributed.
This is called the normal

00:47:21.485 --> 00:47:27.302
distribution or the Gaussian
distribution--it's a continuous

00:47:27.302 --> 00:47:29.878
distribution.
I think you've heard of this,

00:47:29.878 --> 00:47:32.238
right?
This is high school raw

00:47:32.238 --> 00:47:35.481
material.
But I want to emphasize that

00:47:35.481 --> 00:47:38.880
there are also other bell-shaped
curves.

00:47:38.880 --> 00:47:41.538
This is the most famous
bell-shaped curve,

00:47:41.538 --> 00:47:45.039
but there are other ones with
different mathematics.

00:47:45.039 --> 00:47:49.022
A particular interest in
finance is fat-tailed

00:47:49.022 --> 00:47:50.350
alternatives.

00:47:55.840 --> 00:47:59.249
It could be that a random
distribution--I don't have

00:47:59.249 --> 00:48:01.590
colored chalk here I don't
think,

00:48:01.590 --> 00:48:05.276
so I will use a dash line to
represent the fat-tailed

00:48:05.276 --> 00:48:08.286
distribution.
Suppose the distribution looks

00:48:08.286 --> 00:48:09.000
like this.

00:48:13.019 --> 00:48:17.651
Then I have to try to do that
on the other side,

00:48:17.651 --> 00:48:22.893
as symmetrically as I can.
These are the tails of the

00:48:22.893 --> 00:48:28.494
distribution;
this is the right tail and this

00:48:28.494 --> 00:48:33.763
is the left tail.
You can see that the dash

00:48:33.763 --> 00:48:38.791
distribution I drew has more out
in the tails,

00:48:38.791 --> 00:48:44.223
so we call it fat-tailed.
This refers to random variables

00:48:44.223 --> 00:48:48.014
that have fat-tailed
distributions--random variables

00:48:48.014 --> 00:48:51.730
that occasionally give you
really big outcomes.

00:48:51.730 --> 00:48:55.413
You have a chance of being way
out here with a fat-tailed

00:48:55.413 --> 00:48:58.035
distribution.
It's a very important

00:48:58.035 --> 00:49:02.554
observation in finance that
returns on a lot of speculative

00:49:02.554 --> 00:49:05.670
assets have fat-tailed
distributions.

00:49:05.670 --> 00:49:09.751
That means that you can go
through twenty years of a career

00:49:09.751 --> 00:49:13.973
on Wall Street and all you've
observed is observations in the

00:49:13.973 --> 00:49:16.729
central region.
So you feel that you know

00:49:16.729 --> 00:49:19.996
pretty well how things behave;
but then, all of a sudden,

00:49:19.996 --> 00:49:23.683
there's something way out here.
This would be good luck if you

00:49:23.683 --> 00:49:27.474
were long and now suddenly you
got a huge return that you would

00:49:27.474 --> 00:49:30.836
not have thought was possible
since you've never seen it

00:49:30.836 --> 00:49:33.581
before.
But you can also have an

00:49:33.581 --> 00:49:36.868
incredibly bad return.
This complicates finance

00:49:36.868 --> 00:49:39.019
because it means that you never
know.

00:49:39.019 --> 00:49:44.727
You never have enough
experience to get through all

00:49:44.727 --> 00:49:50.087
these things.
It's a big complication in

00:49:50.087 --> 00:49:52.789
finance.
My friend Nassim Talib has just

00:49:52.789 --> 00:49:55.205
written a book about it
called--maybe I'll talk about

00:49:55.205 --> 00:49:56.969
that--called The Black
Swan.

00:49:56.969 --> 00:50:02.832
It's about how so many plans in
finance are messed up by rare

00:50:02.832 --> 00:50:07.230
events that suddenly appear out
of nowhere.

00:50:07.230 --> 00:50:10.075
He called it The Black
Swan because if you look at

00:50:10.075 --> 00:50:13.860
swans, they're always white.
You've never seen a black swan.

00:50:13.860 --> 00:50:16.535
So, you end up going through
life assuming that there are no

00:50:16.535 --> 00:50:18.132
black swans.
But, in fact,

00:50:18.132 --> 00:50:21.170
there are and you might finally
see one.

00:50:21.170 --> 00:50:24.126
You don't want to predicate
making complicated gambles under

00:50:24.126 --> 00:50:26.079
the assumption that they don't
exist.

00:50:26.079 --> 00:50:31.083
Talib, who's a Wall Street
professional,

00:50:31.083 --> 00:50:38.140
talks about these black swans
as being the real story of

00:50:38.140 --> 00:50:40.159
finance.
Now.

00:50:40.159 --> 00:50:44.944
I want to move away from
statistics and talk about

00:50:44.944 --> 00:50:49.045
present values,
which is another concept in

00:50:49.045 --> 00:50:55.418
finance that is fundamental.
And so, let me--And then this

00:50:55.418 --> 00:51:02.040
will conclude today's lecture.
What is a present value?

00:51:06.789 --> 00:51:09.815
This isn't really statistics
anymore, but it's a concept that

00:51:09.815 --> 00:51:11.630
I want to include in this
lecture.

00:51:11.630 --> 00:51:17.907
People in business often have
claims on future money,

00:51:17.907 --> 00:51:21.424
not money today.
For example,

00:51:21.424 --> 00:51:28.261
I may have someone who promises
to pay me $1 in one year or in

00:51:28.261 --> 00:51:34.538
two years or three years.
The present value is what

00:51:34.538 --> 00:51:38.856
that's worth today.
I may have an "IOU" from

00:51:38.856 --> 00:51:43.599
someone or I may own a bond from
someone that promises to pay me

00:51:43.599 --> 00:51:46.309
something in a year or two
years.

00:51:46.309 --> 00:51:50.543
According to a time-honored
tradition in finance,

00:51:50.543 --> 00:51:55.747
it says that it's a promise to
pay $1, but it's not worth $1

00:51:55.747 --> 00:51:59.929
today.
It must be worth less than $1.

00:51:59.929 --> 00:52:06.004
What you could do hundreds of
years ago--and can still do it

00:52:06.004 --> 00:52:11.666
today--was go to a bank and
present this bond or IOU and

00:52:11.666 --> 00:52:15.920
say,
"What will you give me for it?"

00:52:15.920 --> 00:52:26.307
The bank will discount it.
Sometimes we say "present

00:52:26.307 --> 00:52:27.650
discounted value."

00:52:31.239 --> 00:52:34.277
The banker will say,
"Well you have $1 a year from

00:52:34.277 --> 00:52:38.119
now, but that's a year from now,
so I won't give you $1 now.

00:52:38.119 --> 00:52:42.039
I'll give you the present
discounted value for it."

00:52:42.039 --> 00:52:45.260
Now, I'm going to abstract from
risk.

00:52:45.260 --> 00:52:48.033
Let's assume that we know that
this thing is going to be paid,

00:52:48.033 --> 00:52:49.579
so it's a matter of simple
time.

00:52:49.579 --> 00:52:53.187
Of course, the banker isn't
going to give you $1 for

00:52:53.187 --> 00:52:57.502
something that is paying $1 in a
year because the banker knows

00:52:57.502 --> 00:53:01.110
that $1 could be invested at the
interest rate.

00:53:01.110 --> 00:53:12.308
Let's say the interest rate is
r and that would be a

00:53:12.308 --> 00:53:17.714
number like .05,
which is 5%,

00:53:17.714 --> 00:53:25.630
which is five divided by one
hundred.

00:53:25.630 --> 00:53:37.441
Then the present value of
$1--The present PDV or PV of $1

00:53:37.441 --> 00:53:44.996
= $1/(1+r).
That's because the banker is

00:53:44.996 --> 00:53:52.147
thinking, if I have this amount
right now and I invest it for

00:53:52.147 --> 00:53:57.236
one year, then what do I have.
I have (1 +

00:53:57.236 --> 00:54:01.599
r)*(1/1+r).
It's $1, so that works out

00:54:01.599 --> 00:54:04.679
exactly right.
You have to discount something

00:54:04.679 --> 00:54:09.099
that's one period in the future
by dividing it by 1+r.

00:54:09.099 --> 00:54:14.807
This is the present value of $1
in one time period,

00:54:14.807 --> 00:54:20.449
which I'm taking to be a year.
It doesn't have to be a year.

00:54:20.449 --> 00:54:24.972
The interest rate has units of
time, so I have to specify a

00:54:24.972 --> 00:54:29.340
time period over which I'm
measuring an interest rate.

00:54:29.340 --> 00:54:35.001
Typically it's a year.
If it's a one-year interest

00:54:35.001 --> 00:54:43.575
rate, the time period is one
year, and the present value of

00:54:43.575 --> 00:54:52.741
$1 in one time period is given
by this: the present value of $1

00:54:52.741 --> 00:55:00.280
in n periods is
1/(1+r)^(n) and that's

00:55:00.280 --> 00:55:04.420
all there is to this.

00:55:10.210 --> 00:55:16.960
I want to talk about valuing
streams of payments.

00:55:16.960 --> 00:55:22.316
Suppose someone has a contract
that promises to pay an amount

00:55:22.316 --> 00:55:25.619
each period over a number of
years.

00:55:25.619 --> 00:55:35.534
We have formulas for these
present values and these

00:55:35.534 --> 00:55:42.333
formulas are well known.
I'm just going to go through

00:55:42.333 --> 00:55:47.885
them rather quickly here.
The simplest thing is something

00:55:47.885 --> 00:55:51.910
called a consol or perpetuity.

00:55:57.039 --> 00:56:02.806
A perpetuity is an asset or a
contract that pays a fixed

00:56:02.806 --> 00:56:07.420
amount of money each time
period, forever.

00:56:07.420 --> 00:56:11.713
We call them consols because,
in the early 1700s,

00:56:11.713 --> 00:56:16.722
the British Government issued
what they called consols or

00:56:16.722 --> 00:56:22.447
consolidated debt of the British
Crown that paid a certain amount

00:56:22.447 --> 00:56:26.829
of pound sterling every six
months forever.

00:56:26.829 --> 00:56:29.395
You may say,
what audacity for the British

00:56:29.395 --> 00:56:32.400
Government to promise to pay
anything forever.

00:56:32.400 --> 00:56:35.339
Will they be around forever?
Well as far as you're

00:56:35.339 --> 00:56:38.469
concerned, it's as good as
forever, right?

00:56:38.469 --> 00:56:41.036
Maybe someday the
British--United

00:56:41.036 --> 00:56:45.687
Kingdom--something will happen
to it, it will fall apart or

00:56:45.687 --> 00:56:48.361
change;
but that is so distant in the

00:56:48.361 --> 00:56:51.760
future that we can disregard
that, so we'll take that as

00:56:51.760 --> 00:56:54.158
forever.
Anyway, the government might

00:56:54.158 --> 00:56:56.735
buy them back too,
so who cares if it isn't

00:56:56.735 --> 00:56:58.857
forever.
Let's just talk about it as

00:56:58.857 --> 00:57:03.334
forever.
Let's say this thing pays one

00:57:03.334 --> 00:57:09.300
pound a period forever.
What is the present value of

00:57:09.300 --> 00:57:12.998
that?
Well, the first--each payment

00:57:12.998 --> 00:57:19.579
we'll call a coupon--so it pays
one pound one year from now.

00:57:19.579 --> 00:57:22.119
Let's say it's one year just to
simplify things.

00:57:22.119 --> 00:57:26.729
It pays another pound two years
from now, it pays another pound

00:57:26.729 --> 00:57:30.225
three years from now.
The present value is equal

00:57:30.225 --> 00:57:34.345
to--remember it starts one year
from now under assumption--we

00:57:34.345 --> 00:57:38.260
could do it differently but I'm
assuming one year now.

00:57:38.260 --> 00:57:45.320
The present value is
1/(1+r) for the first

00:57:45.320 --> 00:57:51.547
year;
plus for the second year it's

00:57:51.547 --> 00:57:58.260
1/(1+r)²;
for the third year it's

00:57:58.260 --> 00:58:03.449
1/(1+r)³;
and that goes on forever.

00:58:03.449 --> 00:58:08.023
That's an infinite series and
you know how to sum that,

00:58:08.023 --> 00:58:10.762
I think.
I'll tell you what it is:

00:58:10.762 --> 00:58:13.034
it's 1/r,
or it would be

00:58:13.034 --> 00:58:16.890
£1/r .
Generally, if it pays c

00:58:16.890 --> 00:58:20.176
dollars for every period,
the present value is

00:58:20.176 --> 00:58:24.525
c/r.
That's the formula for the

00:58:24.525 --> 00:58:28.855
present value of a consol.
That's one of the most basic

00:58:28.855 --> 00:58:32.551
formulas in finance.
The interesting thing is that

00:58:32.551 --> 00:58:37.561
it means that the value of
consol moves inversely to the

00:58:37.561 --> 00:58:40.816
interest rate.
The British Government issued

00:58:40.816 --> 00:58:44.523
those consols in the early 1700s
and, while they were refinanced

00:58:44.523 --> 00:58:47.760
in the late nineteenth century,
they're still there.

00:58:47.760 --> 00:58:51.842
If you want to go out and buy
one, you can get on your laptop

00:58:51.842 --> 00:58:55.039
right after this lecture and buy
one of them.

00:58:55.039 --> 00:58:58.210
Then you've got something that
will pay you something forever.

00:58:58.210 --> 00:59:02.094
But you're going to know that
the value of that in the market

00:59:02.094 --> 00:59:04.489
moves opposite with interest
rates.

00:59:04.489 --> 00:59:07.480
So, if interest rates go down,
the value goes up;

00:59:07.480 --> 00:59:10.210
if interest rates go up,
the value of your investment

00:59:10.210 --> 00:59:15.297
goes down.
Another formula is--what if the

00:59:15.297 --> 00:59:23.492
consol doesn't pay--I'm sorry,
the next thing is a growing

00:59:23.492 --> 00:59:24.930
consol.

00:59:28.079 --> 00:59:31.596
I'm calling it a growing consol
even though the British consols

00:59:31.596 --> 00:59:33.815
didn't grow.
Let's say that the British

00:59:33.815 --> 00:59:37.050
Government didn't say that
they'll pay one pound per year,

00:59:37.050 --> 00:59:44.000
but it'll be one pound the
first year, then it will grow at

00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:51.550
the rate g and it will
eventually be infinitely large.

00:59:51.550 --> 01:00:02.373
You get one pound the first
year, you get 1+g pounds

01:00:02.373 --> 01:00:09.838
the second year,
etc., (1+g)²

01:00:09.838 --> 01:00:16.900
the third year and so on.
The present value of

01:00:16.900 --> 01:00:21.849
this--suppose it pays--let's say
it pays c pounds each

01:00:21.849 --> 01:00:25.480
year, so it would be c
times this.

01:00:25.480 --> 01:00:29.403
It would be c times
(1+g)³

01:00:29.403 --> 01:00:33.772
in the third year,
etc., Then the present value is

01:00:33.772 --> 01:00:38.854
equal to c/(r-
g)--that's the formula

01:00:38.854 --> 01:00:42.510
for the value of a growing
console.

01:00:42.510 --> 01:00:46.432
g has to be less than
r for this to make sense

01:00:46.432 --> 01:00:50.355
because if g--if it's
growing faster than the rate of

01:00:50.355 --> 01:00:53.469
interest,
then this infinite series will

01:00:53.469 --> 01:00:56.920
not converge and the value would
be infinite.

01:00:56.920 --> 01:00:59.706
You might ask,
"Well then how does that make

01:00:59.706 --> 01:01:02.665
sense?"
What if the British Government

01:01:02.665 --> 01:01:07.496
promised to pay 10% more each
year, how would the market value

01:01:07.496 --> 01:01:09.995
that?
The formula doesn't have a

01:01:09.995 --> 01:01:12.410
number.
I'll tell you why it doesn't

01:01:12.410 --> 01:01:15.106
have a number:
the British Government will

01:01:15.106 --> 01:01:18.722
never promise to pay you 10%
more each year because they

01:01:18.722 --> 01:01:21.225
can't do it.
And, the market wouldn't

01:01:21.225 --> 01:01:24.748
believe them because you can't
grow every year faster than the

01:01:24.748 --> 01:01:27.325
interest rate.
Now that's one of the most

01:01:27.325 --> 01:01:29.290
basic lessons,
you can't do it.

01:01:33.940 --> 01:01:37.116
One more thing that I think
would be relevant to

01:01:37.116 --> 01:01:39.820
the--there's also the annuity
formula.

01:01:39.820 --> 01:01:48.398
This is a formula that applies
to--what if an asset pays a

01:01:48.398 --> 01:01:54.870
fixed amount every period and
then stops?

01:01:54.870 --> 01:02:02.301
That's called an annuity.
An annuity pays c

01:02:02.301 --> 01:02:16.824
dollars starting in t =
1,2, 3, and n is the last

01:02:16.824 --> 01:02:25.452
period, then it stops.
A good example of an annuity is

01:02:25.452 --> 01:02:28.871
a mortgage on a house.
When you buy a house,

01:02:28.871 --> 01:02:32.633
you borrow the money and you
pay it back in fixed--it would

01:02:32.633 --> 01:02:36.070
usually be monthly,
but let's say annual payments.

01:02:36.070 --> 01:02:40.844
You pay every year a fixed
amount on your house to the

01:02:40.844 --> 01:02:45.979
mortgage originator and then
after so many--n is 30

01:02:45.979 --> 01:02:51.254
years,
typically--you would then have

01:02:51.254 --> 01:02:54.874
paid it off.
It used to be that mortgages

01:02:54.874 --> 01:02:57.829
had what's called a balloon
payment at the end.

01:02:57.829 --> 01:03:00.369
This means that you would have
to pay extra money at the end;

01:03:00.369 --> 01:03:02.980
but they decided that people
have trouble doing that.

01:03:02.980 --> 01:03:06.079
It's much better to pay a fixed
payment and then you're done.

01:03:06.079 --> 01:03:08.361
Otherwise, if you ask them to
pay more at the end,

01:03:08.361 --> 01:03:10.410
then a lot of people won't have
the money.

01:03:10.410 --> 01:03:16.134
We now have annuity mortgages.
What is the present value of an

01:03:16.134 --> 01:03:22.192
annuity?
That is, the present value of

01:03:22.192 --> 01:03:30.373
an annuity is equal to the
amount--what did I

01:03:30.373 --> 01:03:38.554
say--c*{1 –
[1/(1+r)]^(n)

01:03:38.554 --> 01:03:45.040
}/r.
That is the present value of an

01:03:45.040 --> 01:03:48.448
annuity.
I wanted to say one more thing

01:03:48.448 --> 01:03:53.384
because I realize that you have
to--your first problem set will

01:03:53.384 --> 01:03:58.479
cover this--is to talk about the
concept that applies probability

01:03:58.479 --> 01:04:04.560
theory to Economics.
That is expected utility theory.

01:04:04.560 --> 01:04:09.032
Then I'll conclude with this.
In Economics,

01:04:09.032 --> 01:04:16.619
it is assumed that people have
a utility function,

01:04:16.619 --> 01:04:24.981
which represents how happy they
are with an outcome--we

01:04:24.981 --> 01:04:33.677
typically take that as U,
If I have a monetary outcome,

01:04:33.677 --> 01:04:39.510
then I have a certain amount of
money, x dollars.

01:04:39.510 --> 01:04:46.210
How happy I am with x
dollars is called U(x).

01:04:46.210 --> 01:04:53.603
This, I think you've gotten from
other economics courses--we have

01:04:53.603 --> 01:04:59.380
something called diminishing
marginal utility.

01:05:07.460 --> 01:05:13.931
The idea is that for any amount
of money--if this x is

01:05:13.931 --> 01:05:20.186
the amount of money that I
receive--utility as the function

01:05:20.186 --> 01:05:26.550
of the amount of money I receive
is downwardly-concave.

01:05:26.550 --> 01:05:30.639
The exact shape of the curve is
subject to discussion,

01:05:30.639 --> 01:05:34.960
but the point of diminishing
marginal utility is that,

01:05:34.960 --> 01:05:39.522
as you get more and more money,
the increment in utility for

01:05:39.522 --> 01:05:43.858
each extra dollar diminishes.
Usually we say it never goes

01:05:43.858 --> 01:05:47.389
down, we don't have it going
down, cross that out.

01:05:47.389 --> 01:05:51.000
That would be where having more
money makes you less happy.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:54.208
That may actually work that
way, but our theory says no,

01:05:54.208 --> 01:05:57.591
you always want more.
It's always upward sloping,

01:05:57.591 --> 01:06:01.448
but it may, after awhile,
you get close to satiation

01:06:01.448 --> 01:06:04.523
where you've got enough.
Incidentally,

01:06:04.523 --> 01:06:08.736
I mentioned this last time--I
was talking about--I was

01:06:08.736 --> 01:06:13.744
philosophizing about wealth and
I asked what are you going to do

01:06:13.744 --> 01:06:17.635
with a billion dollars.
We have many billionaires in

01:06:17.635 --> 01:06:21.084
this country and I think that
the only thing you have to do

01:06:21.084 --> 01:06:24.232
with it is philanthropy.
They have to give it away

01:06:24.232 --> 01:06:26.639
because they are essentially
satiated.

01:06:26.639 --> 01:06:29.087
Because, as I said,
you can only drive one car at a

01:06:29.087 --> 01:06:31.436
time and if you've got ten of
them in the garage,

01:06:31.436 --> 01:06:33.590
then it doesn't really do you
much good.

01:06:33.590 --> 01:06:36.789
You can't do it;
you can't enjoy all ten of them.

01:06:36.789 --> 01:06:41.019
It's important--that's one
reason why we want policies that

01:06:41.019 --> 01:06:44.301
encourage equality of
incomes--not necessarily

01:06:44.301 --> 01:06:46.164
equality,
but reasonable

01:06:46.164 --> 01:06:50.085
equality--because the people
with very low wealth have a very

01:06:50.085 --> 01:06:54.202
high marginal utility of income
and people with very high wealth

01:06:54.202 --> 01:06:57.716
have very little.
So, if you take from the rich

01:06:57.716 --> 01:07:01.010
and give to the poor you make
people happier.

01:07:01.010 --> 01:07:05.349
We're not going to do that in a
Robin Hood way;

01:07:05.349 --> 01:07:08.320
but in finance we're going to
do that in a systematic way

01:07:08.320 --> 01:07:11.891
through risk management.
We're going to be taking away

01:07:11.891 --> 01:07:15.745
from lucky--you think of
yourself as randomly on any

01:07:15.745 --> 01:07:18.652
point of this.
You don't want--you know that

01:07:18.652 --> 01:07:21.393
you'd like to take money away
from yourself in the

01:07:21.393 --> 01:07:24.694
high-outcome years and give it
to yourself in the low-income

01:07:24.694 --> 01:07:28.135
years.
What finance theory is based

01:07:28.135 --> 01:07:33.988
on--and much of economics is
based on--the idea that people

01:07:33.988 --> 01:07:39.739
want to maximize the expected
utility of their wealth.

01:07:39.739 --> 01:07:43.874
Since this is a concave
function, it's not just the

01:07:43.874 --> 01:07:47.049
expected value.
To calculate the expected

01:07:47.049 --> 01:07:50.801
utility of your wealth,
you might also have to look at

01:07:50.801 --> 01:07:54.771
the expected return,
or the geometric expected

01:07:54.771 --> 01:07:58.050
return, or the standard
deviation.

01:07:58.050 --> 01:07:59.679
Or you might have to look at
the fat tail.

01:07:59.679 --> 01:08:03.188
There are so many different
aspects that we can get into and

01:08:03.188 --> 01:08:06.460
this underlying theory motivates
a lot of what we do.

01:08:06.460 --> 01:08:11.906
But it's not a complete theory
until we specify the utility

01:08:11.906 --> 01:08:14.475
function.
Of course, we will also be

01:08:14.475 --> 01:08:17.960
talking about behavioral finance
in this course and we'll,

01:08:17.960 --> 01:08:21.624
at times, be saying that the
utility function concept isn't

01:08:21.624 --> 01:08:25.224
always right--the idea that
people are actually maximizing

01:08:25.224 --> 01:08:28.510
expected utility might not be
entirely accurate.

01:08:28.510 --> 01:08:31.609
But, in terms of the basic
theory, that's the core concept.

01:08:31.609 --> 01:08:35.830
I have one question on the
problem set that asks you to

01:08:35.830 --> 01:08:40.909
think about how you would handle
a decision: whether to gamble,

01:08:40.909 --> 01:08:45.680
based on efficient--based on
expected utility theory.

01:08:45.680 --> 01:08:50.270
That's a little bit of a tricky
question but--So,

01:08:50.270 --> 01:08:55.913
do the best you can on it and
think--try to think about what

01:08:55.913 --> 01:09:01.460
this kind of theory would imply
for gambling behavior.

